    870hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.5hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3.5.xmlEquation2.1.3.5hodge-theory-ii-2.1.3         N\circ  w         = (x\mapsto  x^2).       \tag{2.1.3.5}

Let n be an integer. The construction establishes an equivalence of categories between:
the category of real Hodge structures of weight n;
the category of pairs consisting of a real vector space V of finite dimension and of a filtration F on V_\mathbb {C}=\mathbb {C}\otimes _\mathbb {R} V that is n-opposite to its complex conjugate \bar {F}.

A Hodge structure H, of weight n, consists of






        a \mathbb {Z}-module H_\mathbb {Z} of finite type (the "integral lattice");





        a real Hodge structure of weight n on H_\mathbb {R}=\mathbb {R}\otimes _\mathbb {Z} H_\mathbb {Z}.

Hodge structures of weight n form an abelian category. If H is of weight n, and H' is of weight n', then we define a Hodge structure H\otimes H' of weight n+n' by the equations:
(H\otimes H')_\mathbb {Z}=H_\mathbb {Z}\otimes H'_\mathbb {Z};
the action of S on (H\otimes H')_\mathbb {R}=H_\mathbb {R}\otimes H'_\mathbb {R} is the tensor product of the actions of S on H_\mathbb {R} and on H'_\mathbb {R}.

Let X be a compact Kähler variety (for example, smooth and projective). By the holomorphic Poincaré lemma, the de Rham complex \Omega _X^\bullet is a resolution of the constant sheaf \mathbb {C}. We thus have an isomorphism () \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {C}) \sim \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^\bullet (X,\Omega _X^\bullet ) and the stupid filtration on \Omega _X^\bullet () defines the hypercohomology spectral sequence
